{"term":"2011","caseName":"Knox v. Service Employees International Union","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2011/10-1121","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 10, 2012","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/22137","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear argument first this morning in Case 10-1121, Knox v. the Service Employees International Union.","start":0,"stop":9.522,"duration":9.52},{"text":"Mr. Young.","start":9.522,"stop":10.172,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":10.172,"stop":13.058,"duration":2.89},{"text":"Before addressing SEIU's motion to dismiss for mootness, it is important to remember the underlying facts of this case.","start":13.058,"stop":19.562,"duration":6.5},{"text":"For 10 months in 2005 and 2006, more than 36,000 nonmembers, or nearly 40 percent of those employees represented by SEIU employed by the State of California, were compelled to contribute to the SEIU's $12 million Political Fight-Back Fund without being provided the opportunity to challenge the amount of the fee, and to object to its exaction required by the First Amendment.","start":19.562,"stop":43.927,"duration":24.37},{"text":"Adding insult to that injury, the Ninth Circuit said that nonmembers could never say no to contributing to SEIU's political expenditures for ballot propositions, at least Proposition 76.","start":43.927,"stop":56.603,"duration":12.68},{"text":"They have no right to refuse to bankroll that element of SEIU's political speech.","start":56.603,"stop":62.573,"duration":5.97},{"text":"This defies this Court's decisions, distorting the political process on a massive scale.","start":62.573,"stop":68.06,"duration":5.49}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Young, could I ask you to speak to the mootness question first?","start":68.06,"stop":72.346,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"I was just addressing that.","start":72.346,"stop":73.881,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"As -- as I understand your brief, you're -- you're essentially saying that it's impossible to moot a claim for nominal damages.","start":73.881,"stop":81.785,"duration":7.9},{"text":"Is -- is that a correct reading of your position?","start":81.785,"stop":84.904,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure I would go that far, Justice Kagan.","start":84.904,"stop":89.141,"duration":4.24},{"text":"I think in this case, the wishy-washiness, as it were, of the language used by SEIU when it distributed this pasted-on dollar to the class -- or dollars, more accurately -- was inadequate because it failed to represent the importance of the judgment that the nonmember class had won.","start":89.141,"stop":111.971,"duration":22.83}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"So that's a different point, right, which is that the notice was inadequate--","start":111.971,"stop":114.606,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be correct.","start":114.606,"stop":115.791,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"--And when you say \"inadequate\", I read you to be saying sort of not apologetic enough.","start":115.791,"stop":120.843,"duration":5.05},{"text":"And -- in other words, not saying, look, you had a claim against us, we think you're right; it was a valid claim; here is your judgment in satisfaction of that claim; that it didn't forthrightly say that.","start":120.843,"stop":134.937,"duration":14.09},{"text":"But do you think if it had forthrightly said that, we would be living in a different Article III universe?","start":134.937,"stop":141.157,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in this case, Justice Kagan.","start":141.157,"stop":143.776,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Turning to the adequacy of the notice, of the financial disclosure, that did not comply with the district court's judgment, either.","start":143.776,"stop":152.048,"duration":8.27},{"text":"If -- if the only question were the distribution of nominal damages, then perhaps we would be living in that different Article III universe.","start":152.048,"stop":159.218,"duration":7.17},{"text":"But this case is about the judgment of the district court that the SEIU was attempting to comply with.","start":159.218,"stop":166.241,"duration":7.02},{"text":"They failed to do so in virtually all of its elements.","start":166.241,"stop":169.426,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"And how is that?","start":169.426,"stop":171.212,"duration":1.79},{"text":"How did they fail to comply, other than the question of whether they were forthright enough about the fact that they were satisfying the claim?","start":171.212,"stop":178.866,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the district court had ordered -- described the type of notice that it anticipated.","start":178.866,"stop":187.137,"duration":8.27},{"text":"The district court specifically determined that SEIU's subsequent 2006 financial disclosure was inadequate to cure the problem that was caused by the seizure of fees starting in September 2005.","start":187.137,"stop":204.033,"duration":16.9},{"text":"And that is on 73a of the petition appendix B.","start":204.033,"stop":210.42,"duration":6.39},{"text":"The union in this case merely sent the same financial disclosure in the notice that it sent -- to try to moot the case, that it had sent in June of 2006.","start":210.42,"stop":225.362,"duration":14.94},{"text":"Well, the district court had already said this is inadequate.","start":225.362,"stop":228.631,"duration":3.27},{"text":"That seems to me to end the inquiry.","start":228.631,"stop":232,"duration":3.37},{"text":"Obviously, the district court did not contemplate that the notice that was sent in June 2006 satisfied the obligations of its judgment; else it hardly could have ordered a useless act in ordering a new type of notice go out.","start":232,"stop":249.545,"duration":17.54}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And the reason that's important in terms of the content of the notice, the inadequacy, is what?","start":249.545,"stop":254.866,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason that is important, Justice -- Mr. Chief Justice, excuse me -- is that the SEIU is asserting that the case has become moot because it has now complied with the district court's judgment.","start":254.866,"stop":268.423,"duration":13.56}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought -- I thought your argument was that the -- a different type of notice would have resulted in more members electing to opt out, to demand the refund of their assessments?","start":268.423,"stop":281.783,"duration":13.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's certainly one of the possible consequences.","start":281.783,"stop":283.968,"duration":2.19},{"text":"Obviously, I -- we would -- that is speculative to some extent.","start":283.968,"stop":288.337,"duration":4.37},{"text":"But since the purpose of the notice is to provide the information necessary to -- to object, one of the purposes, then we certainly anticipate that there would be more objectors were there to be an -- an adequate notice that complies with the district court's judgment.","start":288.337,"stop":307.083,"duration":18.75}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If the special assessment requires a different kind of notice, and possibly a different kind of opt-in or opt-out regime, would the case be moot?","start":307.083,"stop":316.539,"duration":9.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"If the notice -- I'm sorry, I didn't understand.","start":316.539,"stop":321.574,"duration":5.04}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we're not dealing here with the kind of notice -- with the typical Hudson notice given at the beginning of the year, when the annual dues are collected.","start":321.574,"stop":328.33,"duration":6.76},{"text":"We're dealing with a special assessment.","start":328.33,"stop":329.98,"duration":1.65},{"text":"Now, if a different kind of notice is constitutionally required in that context, would this case be moot?","start":329.98,"stop":336.686,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it would not.","start":336.686,"stop":339.236,"duration":2.55},{"text":"Obviously, we have -- we have -- still have the nominal damages question, and the adequacy of the payment--","start":339.236,"stop":347.292,"duration":8.06}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"My question is whether the -- the different requirements, which presumably were not met here in the context of the special assessment, if there are different requirements in that context, would that be enough to preserve this case as a live controversy?","start":347.292,"stop":361.735,"duration":14.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--So long as the union failed to provide them, and at least in this case, the district court's judgment, we believe, provides an adequate respect for Hudson's underlying requirement, Justice Alito.","start":361.735,"stop":375.228,"duration":13.49}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. -- Mr. Young--","start":375.228,"stop":376.078,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Justice--","start":376.078,"stop":376.745,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--as I understand, the union recognizes that a consequence of mootness would be that the Ninth Circuit judgment is vacated.","start":376.745,"stop":388.719,"duration":11.97},{"text":"Now, if the union would also recognized that that means the district court judgment stays in place, so if the Ninth Circuit judgment is worked out and you're left with the district court judgment as the law of the case, then I think it is moot, isn't it?","start":388.719,"stop":409.966,"duration":21.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, Justice Ginsburg, and this is why: The union would remain free to return to its old ways -- the very type of reason that this Court declined to find mootness in W.T. Grant.","start":409.966,"stop":424.892,"duration":14.93},{"text":"The union has made much -- much of a showing -- or much of a show, more accurately, of the fact that it has changed its internal policy.","start":424.892,"stop":433.331,"duration":8.44},{"text":"It won't do this for 180 days.","start":433.331,"stop":436.616,"duration":3.28},{"text":"But that can hardly be sufficient for this Court to find mootness in this case.","start":436.616,"stop":442.603,"duration":5.99},{"text":"The union made this wonderful and -- and meaningful policy change on 6 days' notice.","start":442.603,"stop":449.193,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But it wasn't -- this case is about a completed episode.","start":449.193,"stop":456.113,"duration":6.92},{"text":"It's about the special assessment that is wrong or right.","start":456.113,"stop":460.584,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true, Justice Ginsburg.","start":460.584,"stop":463.703,"duration":3.12},{"text":"But it is also about the declaratory relief that was ordered by -- that was entered by the district court.","start":463.703,"stop":468.671,"duration":4.97},{"text":"It is about the -- which was virtually injunctive relief in this case.","start":468.671,"stop":472.308,"duration":3.64},{"text":"It is also about the effect of that judgment for future activities, and how that will affect the way SEIU operates.","start":472.308,"stop":482.83,"duration":10.52}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it have--","start":482.83,"stop":483.614,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, are you saying that it's capable of repetition, yet aiding review?","start":483.614,"stop":487.234,"duration":3.62},{"text":"I'm not quite sure.","start":487.234,"stop":488.018,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"It would certainly be so in this case, Justice Kennedy.","start":488.018,"stop":490.686,"duration":2.67},{"text":"The union set a very short time -- well, a relatively short time period, given the length of time a case comes up from the courts as a rule in this Court.","start":490.686,"stop":503.678,"duration":12.99}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the injunction have future -- future terms?","start":503.678,"stop":505.863,"duration":2.19},{"text":"Is it a permanent injunction or is it just an injunction that relates to the notice that is required in this case?","start":505.863,"stop":511.449,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Just -- just to be clear, there is -- I'm talking about something that's tantamount to an injunction, Justice Kennedy.","start":511.449,"stop":517.753,"duration":6.3},{"text":"It wasn't actually phrased as an injunction.","start":517.753,"stop":520.372,"duration":2.62},{"text":"It was an affirmative, ordering an affirmative act.","start":520.372,"stop":524.591,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"But isn't that important, Mr. Young, because usually where we've talked about capable repetition, or where we've talked about the same thing could happen again, it's where an injunction has been before us rather than a suit for damages as to a past act.","start":524.591,"stop":540.203,"duration":15.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Justice Kagan, I think that has been generally the case.","start":540.203,"stop":543.405,"duration":3.2},{"text":"I -- in my research, I could find very few cases where it wasn't clear to me that this Court was addressing injunctive relief.","start":543.405,"stop":550.891,"duration":7.49},{"text":"Hudson itself it seems to me did not specifically discuss the entry of injunctive relief in the lower court, and Hudson itself addressed a mootness issue.","start":550.891,"stop":560.014,"duration":9.12},{"text":"If we -- if we talk about these cases in their -- in their strictest sense, the union's notices are all annual, so by the theory that it becomes moot when those notices expire, or potentially moot when those notices expire, this Court would never address these issues, because it would -- I can't imagine one of these cases ever getting up to this Court in as little as a year.","start":560.014,"stop":589.184,"duration":29.17},{"text":"But, the -- this Court in Hudson, in I believe it was footnote 12, said that:","start":589.184,"stop":598.389,"duration":9.21},{"text":"\"This Court reviews the policy, the procedure, the acts as they were defended in the district court. \"","start":598.389,"stop":604.693,"duration":6.3},{"text":"And the union's policy and procedure and acts here were defended in the district court.","start":604.693,"stop":609.93,"duration":5.24},{"text":"And therefore, cases like this should not become moot, because it is capable of repetition and would be evading review simply by the mere limits of how long these policies and procedures are in effect.","start":609.93,"stop":623.023,"duration":13.09}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you make that argument in your opposition?","start":623.023,"stop":624.907,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it seems to me, Justice Kennedy, it is implicit in our argument, although clearly our main point in that argument is that this is a -- a paradigm case of voluntary cessation of allegedly unlawful activity.","start":624.907,"stop":644.62,"duration":19.71},{"text":"Until cert was granted in this case, until the Petitioner's merits brief was filed, SEIU was vigorously defending its practice.","start":644.62,"stop":655.059,"duration":10.44},{"text":"It remained free to impose that practice.","start":655.059,"stop":657.428,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--But that's another -- something quite different than the capable of returning to old ways, because here we do have a discrete episode that's over.","start":657.428,"stop":672.92,"duration":15.49},{"text":"And there was no question that, even though -- what was this, in 2005 -- that the period in 2005-2006, when the special assessment was in effect, that was long over, but you were continuing to litigate it.","start":672.92,"stop":690.315,"duration":17.4},{"text":"And nobody suggested that it would become moot simply because the period was over.","start":690.315,"stop":696.136,"duration":5.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's true, Justice Ginsburg.","start":696.136,"stop":699.005,"duration":2.87},{"text":"Pardon me.","start":699.005,"stop":700.023,"duration":1.02},{"text":"This argument -- this argument was not raised until we were before this Court, the union's argument that the case had somehow become moot, and until it issued a notice--","start":700.023,"stop":710.813,"duration":10.79}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they said that it had become moot because they gave you all the relief you requested, so there was nothing left to the case.","start":710.813,"stop":719.734,"duration":8.92}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, \"all the relief\", Justice Ginsburg, implies that they had complied with the district court's judgment.","start":719.734,"stop":724.305,"duration":4.57},{"text":"As to the notice, we -- we believe that they have not, and -- and we believe that's clear because of the very fact that the district court rejected the 2006 financial disclosure as adequate.","start":724.305,"stop":736.88,"duration":12.58},{"text":"And--","start":736.88,"stop":738.232,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe it's a good point for you to move to the merits.","start":738.232,"stop":740.265,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":740.265,"stop":741.7,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you a question about the merits?","start":741.7,"stop":744.386,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, certainly, Justice Sotomayor.","start":744.386,"stop":746.838,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you attacking the normal system of basing assessments moving forward, based on past accounting and chargeability and non-chargeability?","start":746.838,"stop":762.78,"duration":15.94},{"text":"Or are you just attacking the special assessment?","start":762.78,"stop":766.549,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I appreciate the question, Justice Sotomayor.","start":766.549,"stop":768.834,"duration":2.28},{"text":"No, we are not attacking the normal Hudson procedures.","start":768.834,"stop":773.488,"duration":4.65},{"text":"On--","start":773.488,"stop":774.388,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":774.388,"stop":774.988,"duration":0.6},{"text":"So articulate for me -- what's -- borrowing a phrase from one of my colleagues yesterday, how do we write this opinion?","start":774.988,"stop":783.277,"duration":8.29},{"text":"When is a second Hudson notice required?","start":783.277,"stop":787.813,"duration":4.54},{"text":"Let's presume for the sake of argument that the union had cost overruns.","start":787.813,"stop":795.901,"duration":8.09},{"text":"Labor salaries went up; printing costs went up, not for lobbying; but generally there was a 10 percent increase in their expenses across the board because various contracts that they were involved in required it.","start":795.901,"stop":812.046,"duration":16.15},{"text":"Would you require a second notice in that circumstance?","start":812.046,"stop":815.748,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, Justice Sotomayor.","start":815.748,"stop":818.116,"duration":2.37},{"text":"We would -- we believe -- pardon me -- that a new Hudson notice is required whenever there is a material alteration in the obligations that are imposed upon nonmembers.","start":818.116,"stop":831.174,"duration":13.06},{"text":"The values that--","start":831.174,"stop":833.376,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Articulate that again?","start":833.376,"stop":835.06,"duration":1.68},{"text":"A material change--","start":835.06,"stop":837.577,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--A material increase -- or increase in general terms, in the obligation imposed upon the nonmembers.","start":837.577,"stop":844.767,"duration":7.19},{"text":"In this case I don't think anybody would dispute the 25 percent--","start":844.767,"stop":851.421,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"A material new assessment?","start":851.421,"stop":853.623,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--A material new assessment, yes, Justice Scalia.","start":853.623,"stop":856.741,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":856.741,"stop":857.141,"duration":0.4},{"text":"So we are talking about money here, right?","start":857.141,"stop":858.041,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we are.","start":858.041,"stop":858.725,"duration":0.68},{"text":"Certainly--","start":858.725,"stop":859.175,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":859.175,"stop":859.443,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But without regard to the reason for the assessment?","start":859.443,"stop":864.662,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think as a matter of principle I would have to say yes, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":864.662,"stop":868.966,"duration":4.3},{"text":"The nonmember--","start":868.966,"stop":871.335,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not sure that -- that -- this may just simply be repeating Justice Sotomayor's question, but if they say we have to raise the assessment 10 percent because, as she said, you know, we estimated the printing costs for the union newsletter, whatever, was going to be this and it turns out they raised it, it's going to be that, so we know we are going to have to get additional money for things that are indisputably chargeable, why do you need special procedures in that case?","start":871.335,"stop":903.989,"duration":32.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, it wouldn't be so much a special procedure as a new opportunity to object and challenge the amount of the fee, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":903.989,"stop":910.543,"duration":6.55},{"text":"Certainly one of the elements -- and we recognize, of course, that the primary reason individuals object is political expenditures -- but this Court said very clearly in Abood that people can object for any reason, for no reason, for a good reason, for a bad reason; nobody can inquire as to, why someone objects.","start":910.543,"stop":928.754,"duration":18.21},{"text":"And certainly when a material -- there has been a material increase in the obligation imposed upon nonmembers, they may choose to make an economic decision that heretofore they chose not to make.","start":928.754,"stop":939.645,"duration":10.89},{"text":"They may choose to minimize, particularly the non-objectors, they may choose that they want to minimize the financial obligations they are paying to the union at that time.","start":939.645,"stop":950.268,"duration":10.62}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"It's -- it's peculiar, because in the circumstance where the extra assessment is all going to go to chargeable activities, in fact that means economically speaking the following year the objector will be better off, not worse off, because there is a higher percentage of the total fee that's being paid to chargeable activities.","start":950.268,"stop":974.902,"duration":24.63},{"text":"So this special assessment that Justice Sotomayor and the Chief Justice were talking about is one that will benefit the objector, if he keeps quiet and says nothing.","start":974.902,"stop":985.841,"duration":10.94},{"text":"So it's a little hard to imagine the frame of mind that would say, I need the notice because now I might object whereas I wouldn't have before.","start":985.841,"stop":993.547,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Breyer, the reason for the notice is these people may not trust the union.","start":993.547,"stop":997.899,"duration":4.35},{"text":"They -- they may choose to challenge the amount of the fee.","start":997.899,"stop":1001.052,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I see that point.","start":1001.052,"stop":1002.219,"duration":1.17},{"text":"Can I ask you -- oh, are you -- you want to pursue that further, or are we--","start":1002.219,"stop":1007.039,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Go ahead.","start":1007.039,"stop":1007.456,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--All right.","start":1007.456,"stop":1007.823,"duration":0.37},{"text":"Let me give you this example.","start":1007.823,"stop":1009.573,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":1009.573,"stop":1010.325,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And now I -- but I think I see what your answer is.","start":1010.325,"stop":1014.693,"duration":4.37},{"text":"Imagine it's year 2.","start":1014.693,"stop":1017.312,"duration":2.62},{"text":"In year 1 expenditures broke down so that it was 70 percent chargeable, 30 percent not chargeable.","start":1017.312,"stop":1027.787,"duration":10.48},{"text":"Got that?","start":1027.787,"stop":1028.887,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1028.887,"stop":1029.787,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And normally under Hudson that means in year 2 the deal is, the objectors pay 70 percent, right?","start":1029.787,"stop":1037.993,"duration":8.21}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1037.993,"stop":1039.225,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"In the middle of year 2, surprisingly, something comes up.","start":1039.225,"stop":1047.181,"duration":7.96},{"text":"Something comes up, a surprise to the union, and they want to have a special assessment.","start":1047.181,"stop":1055.937,"duration":8.76},{"text":"And you're saying they just can't without going through this procedure all over again?","start":1055.937,"stop":1061.274,"duration":5.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be correct, Justice Breyer.","start":1061.274,"stop":1063.876,"duration":2.6},{"text":"And now talking about--","start":1063.876,"stop":1066.412,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--Can they take the money that they collected?","start":1066.412,"stop":1069.53,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm sorry?","start":1069.53,"stop":1070.43,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Can they take the money that they collected under the first notice and, instead of doing a special assessment, in the middle of it this campaign gets announced by the governor, and can they then divert the chargeable amount that they have predicted and spend it on the non-chargeable amount?","start":1070.43,"stop":1095.079,"duration":24.65},{"text":"Or are you -- or does that require a second Hudson notice, without a special assessment?","start":1095.079,"stop":1100.466,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand, Justice Sotomayor.","start":1100.466,"stop":1102.085,"duration":1.62},{"text":"And no, under that case I don't believe it would.","start":1102.085,"stop":1104.168,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, so this is a peculiar rule that you have asked us to adopt.","start":1104.168,"stop":1109.655,"duration":5.49},{"text":"The rule is that where there is a special assessment and it will make all the objectors better off, they have to have a special notice that they can object.","start":1109.655,"stop":1119.812,"duration":10.16},{"text":"But where the rule is that we are going to take money we already collected from them and spend it for a totally political purpose, we don't give them a special notice and they don't have to object.","start":1119.812,"stop":1130.652,"duration":10.84},{"text":"Now, that seems totally backwards, but I understand why you get there, and my suspicion is, which you can confirm, is that's the only administrable system you can think of.","start":1130.652,"stop":1140.643,"duration":9.99}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you concede that it is going to make them better off?","start":1140.643,"stop":1143.928,"duration":3.29},{"text":"I would -- I would assume that that's your principal objection.","start":1143.928,"stop":1146.528,"duration":2.6},{"text":"They don't know whether this new assessment is indeed going to be divided the way the original one was or not.","start":1146.528,"stop":1154.367,"duration":7.84},{"text":"They might want to challenge--","start":1154.367,"stop":1155.919,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"That's--","start":1155.919,"stop":1156.769,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--whether -- whether it's all going to be used for -- for assessable activities or not.","start":1156.769,"stop":1161.188,"duration":4.42},{"text":"And they have no -- you are telling me they--","start":1161.188,"stop":1162.722,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1162.722,"stop":1163.239,"duration":0.52},{"text":"But in my--","start":1163.239,"stop":1163.922,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--At the very least, they have to make a -- an interest-free loan to the -- to the union until such time as they can challenge it.","start":1163.922,"stop":1171.495,"duration":7.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, that's exactly correct, Justice Scalia.","start":1171.495,"stop":1173.328,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, but the hypothetical, if I could continue with it, is -- is perhaps unrealistic, but they have 20 bishops and the 14 most honest people in the United States, and they have all absolutely guaranteed and everybody agrees that this goes to chargeable activity.","start":1173.328,"stop":1190.29,"duration":16.96},{"text":"And where I was going with my question, which you see where I was -- you are with me on this, right?","start":1190.29,"stop":1194.527,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1194.527,"stop":1194.861,"duration":0.33},{"text":"Right.","start":1194.861,"stop":1195.311,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And combine the two.","start":1195.311,"stop":1196.244,"duration":0.93},{"text":"What I'm trying to point out and get your response is that you have been forced into this position to create a workable system.","start":1196.244,"stop":1204.816,"duration":8.57},{"text":"Now, why is that workable system one whit better than the workable system we already have, which is all this washes out in a fair manner the following year, that there is an inevitable year's lag, it doesn't work perfectly, but it's as good as any other, and all we have to say is it's better than yours?","start":1204.816,"stop":1228.098,"duration":23.28},{"text":"Now, why is yours better than that?","start":1228.098,"stop":1229.95,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I recall the bishops from the last time I was here, Justice Breyer.","start":1229.95,"stop":1233.402,"duration":3.45},{"text":"I think they made an appearance then.","start":1233.402,"stop":1234.702,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"They are useful to me.","start":1234.702,"stop":1235.954,"duration":1.25},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":1235.954,"stop":1237.038,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"They are, I'm sure.","start":1237.038,"stop":1237.704,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I assume we wouldn't need a Hudson notice at all, if -- if bishops affirmed all of these things, right?","start":1237.704,"stop":1244.293,"duration":6.59},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":1244.293,"stop":1245.343,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"You anticipate my next point, Justice Scalia.","start":1245.343,"stop":1247.159,"duration":1.82},{"text":"These -- these aren't bishops and, with due respect to our litigation opponents in this case, these are people that nonmembers don't trust.","start":1247.159,"stop":1255.982,"duration":8.82},{"text":"These are people with whom nonmembers do not wish to affiliate.","start":1255.982,"stop":1258.351,"duration":2.37},{"text":"And these are people that the nonmembers do not wish to support, and--","start":1258.351,"stop":1263.271,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"The problem is in this system, going back to Justice Breyer's practicality, they will get a chance to object; it just won't be at the moment of the special assessment; it will be the following year.","start":1263.271,"stop":1280.3,"duration":17.03},{"text":"So when the union gives its new notice, it's going to set forth its chargeable and non-chargeable amounts as audited, and it will say, as it did -- as it's done in the briefs before us: On Proposition 76 we are going to take 50 percent as chargeable.","start":1280.3,"stop":1303.848,"duration":23.55},{"text":"And the union members can come in and give a Lehnert objection, those who want to.","start":1303.848,"stop":1310.569,"duration":6.72},{"text":"Those who don't know it's happened and they agree to it.","start":1310.569,"stop":1313.688,"duration":3.12},{"text":"Isn't that correct?","start":1313.688,"stop":1316.406,"duration":2.72},{"text":"They do get a chance to object; the question is the timing.","start":1316.406,"stop":1318.925,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--Then the problem is, Justice Sotomayor, understanding the practice--","start":1318.925,"stop":1323.042,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there an answer to that?","start":1323.042,"stop":1323.977,"duration":0.94},{"text":"They will get a chance to object then?","start":1323.977,"stop":1325.578,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--They will get a chance to object after they have already paid the interest-free loan.","start":1325.578,"stop":1329.363,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's true of the first example I gave you.","start":1329.363,"stop":1332.665,"duration":3.3},{"text":"If something happens in the middle of the year and the union needs to divert already-assessed funds to challenge a election, they can do it and you said that's okay.","start":1332.665,"stop":1347.258,"duration":14.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"And the nonmembers would have the chance to challenge that, but it would be within the normal system of ordinary union dues.","start":1347.258,"stop":1353.579,"duration":6.32},{"text":"We, and I believe this Court in Hudson, presume that any reasonably competent union management would -- would have relatively stable expenditures over the years.","start":1353.579,"stop":1364.369,"duration":10.79}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't -- isn't the premise of Hudson that you give the notice before, before you -- you receive the notice before you have to cough up the money?","start":1364.369,"stop":1373.392,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1373.392,"stop":1374.192,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"And what's now proposed is, well, for -- if there is an additional assessment, you cough up the money first and then later you straighten it out.","start":1374.192,"stop":1382.181,"duration":7.99},{"text":"Do you get -- do you get the interest?","start":1382.181,"stop":1384.8,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"That seems to me to be the problem, Justice Scalia.","start":1384.8,"stop":1386.217,"duration":1.42},{"text":"The people who got the June 2005 notice were left in the dark -- indeed, the union may have been in the dark -- as to this special assessment.","start":1386.217,"stop":1394.989,"duration":8.77},{"text":"But once the union agreed to, decided to impose the special assessment, the union was required by Hudson's principles to shed some light.","start":1394.989,"stop":1405.113,"duration":10.12},{"text":"Perhaps it is less predictive, less accurate, to say: We intend to spend the money this way.","start":1405.113,"stop":1411.1,"duration":5.99},{"text":"But when you have an assessment which is purely intended for politics, and that's what the union said, to create a Political Fight-Back Fund, that's not--","start":1411.1,"stop":1421.223,"duration":10.12}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Does your Hudson notice tell you about what is going to happen next year?","start":1421.223,"stop":1426.277,"duration":5.05},{"text":"I thought your Hudson notice told you this was the breakdown for last year and as far as we can tell that's what it will be next year, but things should change.","start":1426.277,"stop":1435.55,"duration":9.27},{"text":"What does the Hudson notice tell you?","start":1435.55,"stop":1439.252,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--The Hudson notice provides you with an opportunity to object and some assurance, because of the audit requirement--","start":1439.252,"stop":1444.989,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But am I right in my description of it?","start":1444.989,"stop":1446.19,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think that would be a fair description, Justice Breyer.","start":1446.19,"stop":1448.809,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they carry over from 1 year to the next, or do you have to refile your objection to the union expenditures every year?","start":1448.809,"stop":1455.563,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Most unions, Mr. Chief Justice, require an annual objection.","start":1455.563,"stop":1460.617,"duration":5.05},{"text":"Now, of course there would be nothing -- we find nothing wrong with an annual challenge requirement if you choose to challenge that year's figures, because obviously it's a specific event.","start":1460.617,"stop":1468.621,"duration":8},{"text":"But most unions seem to require annual objection, so you have to say again and again: I don't want to pay for your politics.","start":1468.621,"stop":1475.46,"duration":6.84},{"text":"But that's not raised in the--","start":1475.46,"stop":1478.26,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But going back to the -- forget about special assessments.","start":1478.26,"stop":1480.579,"duration":2.32},{"text":"I think in one of the briefs, I know in one of the briefs, someone says: Elections happen every 4 years, so in the normal cycle of union activities in an election year they are going to divert more of whatever accessible moneys they have to their lobbying efforts and the following year they will go back to normal for 3 years.","start":1480.579,"stop":1503.694,"duration":23.12},{"text":"You're not challenging that normal variation in the -- in the distribution of the moneys, correct?","start":1503.694,"stop":1514.335,"duration":10.64}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--Correct, Justice Sotomayor.","start":1514.335,"stop":1516.787,"duration":2.45},{"text":"And that, too, may vary from union to union, from State to State even.","start":1516.787,"stop":1519.287,"duration":2.5},{"text":"As some of the Justices I'm sure know, Virginia--","start":1519.287,"stop":1522.822,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So I guess my problem is I don't see how that, given your argument, is any less alone than this special assessment where the labor -- where the objecting members at the end of the year will get notice of what has happened that year, will have an opportunity to place their Lehnert challenges and get them ruled upon, and will, as Justice Breyer said, have a benefit because they are going to either pay more if the Lehnert -- pay less if the Lehnert challenges are upheld or pay more if -- if they're not.","start":1522.822,"stop":1568.434,"duration":45.61},{"text":"But I'm not quite sure how this is a different loan.","start":1568.434,"stop":1571.386,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, we disagree with the union's characterization of its supposed benefit.","start":1571.386,"stop":1577.974,"duration":6.59},{"text":"But, Justice Sotomayor, I see my time has expired and I would like to reserve a balance for rebuttal.","start":1577.974,"stop":1583.71,"duration":5.74},{"text":"I will try address your question more thoroughly when I stand up again.","start":1583.71,"stop":1587.062,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":1587.062,"stop":1587.897,"duration":0.84},{"text":"Mr. Collins.","start":1587.897,"stop":1594.585,"duration":6.69}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court:","start":1594.585,"stop":1597.287,"duration":2.7},{"text":"Justice Ginsburg is absolutely correct that what we have suggested to the Court is that the court of appeals decision be vacated, with the consequence of reinstating the district court judgment.","start":1597.287,"stop":1610.111,"duration":12.82}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Why did you give up once the case was granted here?","start":1610.111,"stop":1612.88,"duration":2.77},{"text":"You didn't consider that until the case came before this Court.","start":1612.88,"stop":1616.599,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor, and the reason for that is when the events in this matter were new and the then union officers' actions were being challenged, the instinct was: We are going to defend the case.","start":1616.599,"stop":1632.043,"duration":15.44},{"text":"And as time went on there was no rethinking of that situation.","start":1632.043,"stop":1638.197,"duration":6.15},{"text":"When the case was granted here over our opposition, noting that we didn't think the questions presented were really presented, the officers of the union, who were not the ones involved in the original case, thought about the situation and came to the realization that they have no stake in the procedures that are at issue here.","start":1638.197,"stop":1660.794,"duration":22.6},{"text":"This is a local that had never done a mid-year increase in the past.","start":1660.794,"stop":1667.049,"duration":6.25},{"text":"What was contemplated as a temporary increase here turned into a permanent increase.","start":1667.049,"stop":1672.601,"duration":5.55},{"text":"The dues went up to 1.5 percent of salary a year after this increase ended.","start":1672.601,"stop":1678.589,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What is this local, and what will the other locals do in the future when special assessments are made?","start":1678.589,"stop":1686.611,"duration":8.02},{"text":"Will they provide notice or will they go back to the old system?","start":1686.611,"stop":1691.165,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"This local -- and I won't belabor the term \"special assessment\" at the moment, but when we get to the merits I think there is a misunderstanding around that, Justice Alito.","start":1691.165,"stop":1700.705,"duration":9.54},{"text":"But this local has put in a procedure which frankly would satisfy the Petitioner s' concerns for the future if future conduct was legitimately at issue here.","start":1700.705,"stop":1714.114,"duration":13.41},{"text":"But it is not, for two reasons.","start":1714.114,"stop":1715.98,"duration":1.87},{"text":"First, when we state that the district court judgment would be reinstated, that's a judgment that was not appealed by the Petitioners.","start":1715.98,"stop":1724.22,"duration":8.24},{"text":"That defines the limits of what they can attain from this case, whatever this Court may decide, and that decision gives whatever protection it gives against future conduct.","start":1724.22,"stop":1736.361,"duration":12.14},{"text":"Now, it gives essentially none for a very good reason.","start":1736.361,"stop":1739.646,"duration":3.28},{"text":"This was a case that has been noted, brought only about a one-time event.","start":1739.646,"stop":1743.532,"duration":3.89},{"text":"There were no allegations of an ongoing practice, there was no request for declaratory or injunctive relief.","start":1743.532,"stop":1749.001,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Collins, as I understand Mr. Young's argument, there is a serious dispute about the adequacy of this notice, and it might be a dispute about whether it was clear enough, about that it was satisfying claims, or it might be a dispute about whether it allowed refunds easily enough, but that Mr. Young is contesting whether the notice complied with the district court's order.","start":1749.001,"stop":1771.951,"duration":22.95},{"text":"Now, as long as that's true, don't we have a live case before us?","start":1771.951,"stop":1776.003,"duration":4.05},{"text":"Somebody has to answer that question about whether your notice complied with the order, and if it's the case that a court has to answer that question, doesn't that depend on the questions presented here, the substantive questions?","start":1776.003,"stop":1789.828,"duration":13.83}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it doesn't, Justice Kagan.","start":1789.828,"stop":1791.964,"duration":2.14},{"text":"The Court's explained in a number of cases, beginning I think with Walling v. Ruder, and also obviously Munsingwear, and U.S. Bank Corp., a case can be in a posture where this Court in disposing of it needs to grant certain relief, clarification of the status of prior orders, and yet the case is moot on the merits such that the Court cannot appropriately reach the merits.","start":1791.964,"stop":1818.432,"duration":26.47},{"text":"That's what we have here.","start":1818.432,"stop":1819.932,"duration":1.5},{"text":"If there is a dispute -- and I will explain in a moment why there really isn't.","start":1819.932,"stop":1823.752,"duration":3.82},{"text":"But if there is a dispute, for example, as to whether an individual failed to get their refund because the notice was inadequate, that dispute is not affected by and requires no decision of this court.","start":1823.752,"stop":1837.809,"duration":14.06},{"text":"If the district court judgment is reinstated then the question of whether we have fully provided all relief called for by that judgment, which we believe we have, would be before the district court's decision.","start":1837.809,"stop":1851.253,"duration":13.44}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But this is not -- this is not an incidental matter.","start":1851.253,"stop":1853.855,"duration":2.6},{"text":"The whole point of your friend's argument with the Hudson notice is they want people to understand what's happening with their union money.","start":1853.855,"stop":1866.179,"duration":12.32},{"text":"And they say this notice didn't let people know that.","start":1866.179,"stop":1869.047,"duration":2.87},{"text":"And if the case is not moot and if they prevail, they will have a right to be heard on what the notice should say.","start":1869.047,"stop":1876.553,"duration":7.51},{"text":"And that will make a difference in how many people opt out or how many people don't.","start":1876.553,"stop":1881.255,"duration":4.7},{"text":"And I guess I'm following up on Justice Kagan's question.","start":1881.255,"stop":1884.374,"duration":3.12},{"text":"That's a very important part of this case, what the notice is going to say, and if we accept your view that it's moot, that issue goes by the wayside.","start":1884.374,"stop":1891.896,"duration":7.52}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's incorrect, Mr. Chief Justice, for two reasons.","start":1891.896,"stop":1895.615,"duration":3.72},{"text":"First of all, the district court required a certain kind of notice to be given.","start":1895.615,"stop":1902.086,"duration":6.47},{"text":"We are stating the district court judgment should be reinstated.","start":1902.086,"stop":1905.304,"duration":3.22},{"text":"If the notice we have given does not comport with what the district court judgment which was not appealed by the Petitioners requires, it will be provided by the district court.","start":1905.304,"stop":1916.195,"duration":10.89},{"text":"We are -- we are not contesting -- the Petitioners are looking a gift horse in the mouth.","start":1916.195,"stop":1920.713,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry, I don't see how that -- I don't see how that works.","start":1920.713,"stop":1922.932,"duration":2.22},{"text":"The notice is only required by the district court if the case is not moot.","start":1922.932,"stop":1930.021,"duration":7.09},{"text":"If the case is moot by the notice you sent out, the district court doesn't have a case on the basis of which to order a different notice.","start":1930.021,"stop":1938.461,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't think that's correct, Your Honor.","start":1938.461,"stop":1940.494,"duration":2.03},{"text":"A case can be moot in this Court and this is what I believe Munsingwear, Walling v. Reuter and the other cases, U.S. Bancorp more recently, explained.","start":1940.494,"stop":1949.666,"duration":9.17},{"text":"At first it seems paradoxical, but it is not paradoxical.","start":1949.666,"stop":1955.053,"duration":5.39},{"text":"A case -- there can be remaining issues potentially in the district court, such as whether the check that the plaintiff paid bounced or not, that could potentially have to be resolved by a district court.","start":1955.053,"stop":1969.246,"duration":14.19},{"text":"And it -- but it means, at least in terms of prudential mootness, there is not a substantive merits issue remaining for the court to be deciding.","start":1969.246,"stop":1979.519,"duration":10.27},{"text":"And it's really quite simple.","start":1979.519,"stop":1981.388,"duration":1.87},{"text":"The Petitioners, as I say.","start":1981.388,"stop":1982.638,"duration":1.25},{"text":"Are looking a gift horse in the mouth.","start":1982.638,"stop":1984.271,"duration":1.63},{"text":"The apex, the acme that they can achieve in this case, is what they got from the district court and it was reversed.","start":1984.271,"stop":1990.91,"duration":6.64},{"text":"We are saying: Give it back to them.","start":1990.91,"stop":1992.96,"duration":2.05},{"text":"Take back the reversal, reinstate the judgment.","start":1992.96,"stop":1995.612,"duration":2.65},{"text":"Whatever they won they will have.","start":1995.612,"stop":1997.731,"duration":2.12},{"text":"We believe we have already given them everything they want.","start":1997.731,"stop":2000.433,"duration":2.7},{"text":"If we have not, the district court will do that.","start":2000.433,"stop":2003.051,"duration":2.62},{"text":"But let me explain the second point, if I may, Mr. Chief Justice, which is that there is no legitimate issue here about whether the notice was adequate.","start":2003.051,"stop":2010.721,"duration":7.67},{"text":"Mr. Young stated quite incorrectly that the notice we have provided is the same as the notice the district court struck down.","start":2010.721,"stop":2021.029,"duration":10.31},{"text":"That's absolutely incorrect.","start":2021.029,"stop":2023.231,"duration":2.2},{"text":"The district court said that the 2005 notice issued before the dues increased obviously did not give specific notice of the dues increase, although it stated that dues could be increased.","start":2023.231,"stop":2035.623,"duration":12.39},{"text":"The district court specifically held at petitioner appendix 73a that the 2006 notice which described the so-called fund and the dues increase and the purposes of it was completely adequate.","start":2035.623,"stop":2051.882,"duration":16.26},{"text":"And the notice the district court -- one also has to realize, the district court was requiring the union to refund only the non-chargeable portion of activities attributed to this increase.","start":2051.882,"stop":2068.16,"duration":16.28},{"text":"A certain kind of notice would be needed for that to justify how the union was computing what it was saying with the chargeable portion to refund.","start":2068.16,"stop":2077.266,"duration":9.11},{"text":"But what the union has done here is provide greater relief than the district court ordered.","start":2077.266,"stop":2080.884,"duration":3.62},{"text":"We have refunded every penny that anyone who requests had paid during the increase.","start":2080.884,"stop":2089.073,"duration":8.19},{"text":"So there is no serious question that the notice that the union sent out, which explained what the increase had been spent on, sufficiently informed individuals as to whether they now want to get back every penny, as we have offered them, of what they paid under the increase.","start":2089.073,"stop":2106.166,"duration":17.09}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I want you to move to the merits.","start":2106.166,"stop":2108.535,"duration":2.37},{"text":"It may be a good time to do that.","start":2108.535,"stop":2111.07,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2111.07,"stop":2111.703,"duration":0.63},{"text":"Turning to the merits--","start":2111.703,"stop":2114.522,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I clarify a point?","start":2114.522,"stop":2116.557,"duration":2.03},{"text":"I thought I heard and maybe I just didn't look at the union regulations, the new ones.","start":2116.557,"stop":2124.045,"duration":7.49},{"text":"Is it limited to 180 days?","start":2124.045,"stop":2126.68,"duration":2.63},{"text":"I thought I heard your adversary say that the--","start":2126.68,"stop":2129.464,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, it has a provision that it can't be repealed without a 180-day notice.","start":2129.464,"stop":2138.137,"duration":8.67},{"text":"There can't, can't be a sudden repeal of the new procedure.","start":2138.137,"stop":2140.672,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--I see.","start":2140.672,"stop":2141.422,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"But I do want to make clear, we think nothing -- our position on mootness is not dependent on the Court determining that the new procedure will be in effect forever.","start":2141.422,"stop":2151.98,"duration":10.56},{"text":"Our position--","start":2151.98,"stop":2152.664,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you tell me what the burden is on the union to give a second Hudson notice whenever there is a special assessment?","start":2152.664,"stop":2161.586,"duration":8.92},{"text":"Meaning do you happen to know how frequently unions impose special assessments and what the incremental cost is to the union of giving such notice?","start":2161.586,"stop":2174.845,"duration":13.26}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--That requires a fairly extensive answer, I believe, Justice Sotomayor, partly because--","start":2174.845,"stop":2182.083,"duration":7.24}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Try to summarize it.","start":2182.083,"stop":2183.349,"duration":1.27},{"text":"I wasn't looking to monopolize you.","start":2183.349,"stop":2184.835,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--I believe -- I believe the word \"special assessment\" is being used here with a meaning that doesn't correspond to what this union did.","start":2184.835,"stop":2192.489,"duration":7.65},{"text":"I can say this much: There has never -- there's been only one other case in any Federal court that I am aware of, and only in a district court, there's been no other appellate court, dealing with any kind of assessment, temporary dues increase and how it affects Hudson rights.","start":2192.489,"stop":2209.05,"duration":16.56},{"text":"So this is a non-event in the real world.","start":2209.05,"stop":2215.787,"duration":6.74},{"text":"There are no challenges that have been made previously to any kinds of assessments or increases.","start":2215.787,"stop":2223.876,"duration":8.09},{"text":"But unions use assessments in two -- in many different ways.","start":2223.876,"stop":2228.012,"duration":4.14},{"text":"And let me contrast one way with what happened here, and I think it will show why there is no serious question here about a need for a notice.","start":2228.012,"stop":2239.886,"duration":11.87},{"text":"Some unions have a dues structure which covers only certain kinds of activities.","start":2239.886,"stop":2246.04,"duration":6.15},{"text":"And they contemplate a new kind of activity that they would not normally pay for out of dues or fees.","start":2246.04,"stop":2253.495,"duration":7.45},{"text":"They say often with a vote, which was not required here.","start":2253.495,"stop":2257.863,"duration":4.37},{"text":"There was no vote required or taken here of bargaining unit members for what occurred in this instance.","start":2257.863,"stop":2264.767,"duration":6.9},{"text":"But you may have a union that says: We want to make the kind of expenditure that's really unanticipated.","start":2264.767,"stop":2269.671,"duration":4.9},{"text":"It's not what we normally do with our dues.","start":2269.671,"stop":2271.457,"duration":1.79},{"text":"We are going to put it to a vote.","start":2271.457,"stop":2273.057,"duration":1.6},{"text":"If you approve it, we will collect it, we'll probably put it in a segregated fund separate from our treasury.","start":2273.057,"stop":2279.044,"duration":5.99},{"text":"That kind of an assessment can raise potential issues, I would acknowledge, under Hudson.","start":2279.044,"stop":2287.233,"duration":8.19},{"text":"It's worlds away from what we have here because all that happened in this case was that the union increased from 1 percent to 1.25 percent of salary, the regular membership dues, and the fees based on those dues that were deducted by employers and paid into the union's general treasury--","start":2287.233,"stop":2307.98,"duration":20.75}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it incorrect that this was for what was termed a \"Political Fight-Back Fund\"?","start":2307.98,"stop":2312.95,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--It was -- some union communications described it as having that sole -- that purpose.","start":2312.95,"stop":2322.573,"duration":9.62},{"text":"The October 27th letter, which was the most detailed explanation, said it had two purposes, basically to fight back at the bargaining table and to fight back politically.","start":2322.573,"stop":2332.261,"duration":9.69},{"text":"But what's essential, Justice Alito, it was never suggested nor was it ever the case that this money would be in any way segregated or treated as a separate entity so to speak.","start":2332.261,"stop":2344.736,"duration":12.47},{"text":"So we have the Schermerhorn problem here.","start":2344.736,"stop":2347.605,"duration":2.87},{"text":"Basically, Petitioners' position is based on the fallacy exposed in Schermerhorn of trying to take part of a unified general treasury and treat it as if it were a distinct entity, because--","start":2347.605,"stop":2359.246,"duration":11.64}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me give you this example and maybe you will say that this is different from your case and the rules should be different in these two cases.","start":2359.246,"stop":2366.085,"duration":6.84},{"text":"The annual dues for a particular -- for members of this union are 1 percent of their salaries and let's say that amounts to -- or it's a certain percentage of their salaries, and let's say that amounts to $500 annual dues.","start":2366.085,"stop":2383.11,"duration":17.03},{"text":"And let's say that in the prior year 90 percent of the money collected by the union was used for chargeable purposes, 10 percent for non-chargeable purposes.","start":2383.11,"stop":2391.883,"duration":8.77},{"text":"So someone who objected, a nonmember who objected, would be able to get back $50.","start":2391.883,"stop":2398.639,"duration":6.76},{"text":"Now, during the course of the year the union levies a special assessment or whatever you want to call it, and for this 90 -- the percentages are exactly reversed.","start":2398.639,"stop":2411.797,"duration":13.16},{"text":"90 percent is for non-chargeable, 10 percent is for chargeable.","start":2411.797,"stop":2415.648,"duration":3.85},{"text":"So now a member who potentially wants to object has $450 at stake.","start":2415.648,"stop":2423.087,"duration":7.44},{"text":"Now, in that situation, why shouldn't there be separate notice?","start":2423.087,"stop":2426.806,"duration":3.72},{"text":"Aren't the economic incentives quite different?","start":2426.806,"stop":2429.341,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--If I understand the hypothetical, there could be a problem there if the assumption is then that the union really is beginning a kind of spending that's really foreign to the way it's spent money in the past.","start":2429.341,"stop":2446.453,"duration":17.11},{"text":"What needs to be explained here, though, Justice Alito, is I don't think one would guess from anything that has been said today that we are talking about a period of time when the union's chargeable spending increased and its non-chargeable spending decreased.","start":2446.453,"stop":2463.914,"duration":17.46},{"text":"We are talking about a period of time when objecting nonmembers did not even pay their pro rata share of the concededly chargeable expenditures, meaning they did not pay one penny for any political activities.","start":2463.914,"stop":2477.139,"duration":13.22}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I said, my hypothetical may be very different from what happened here, and maybe it's an unrealistic hypothetical and you can answer that.","start":2477.139,"stop":2485.245,"duration":8.11},{"text":"But if it were to occur, should there not be Hudson notice?","start":2485.245,"stop":2489.297,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the problem -- it would be a closer question, but I think not, because again it would be caught up in the subsequent year.","start":2489.297,"stop":2502.873,"duration":13.58}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But what if the money is going to be used for an election campaign?","start":2502.873,"stop":2507.491,"duration":4.62},{"text":"What if it is going to be used to weigh in, in favor of one gubernatorial candidate against another, in favor of one slate of legislative candidates against another.","start":2507.491,"stop":2518.049,"duration":10.56},{"text":"And on those issues, the nonmembers may have very strong partisan and ideological objections.","start":2518.049,"stop":2524.969,"duration":6.92},{"text":"So why should they not be given a notice at that time--","start":2524.969,"stop":2528.005,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"It would depend--","start":2528.005,"stop":2528.821,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--and given the opportunity not to give what would be at a minimum an interest-free loan for the purposes of influencing an election campaign?","start":2528.821,"stop":2538.11,"duration":9.29}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--It would depend, Justice Alito.","start":2538.11,"stop":2539.878,"duration":1.77},{"text":"I think in your hypothetical, one might be able to say -- there might be more facts needed, but one might be able to say that what is occurring is something that could not be anticipated reasonably by the person who got the notice.","start":2539.878,"stop":2553.472,"duration":13.59},{"text":"In this case, however -- and this is crucial to this case -- the notice in 2005 told every nonmember that, of our $38 million budget, we spent 43.6 percent of it last year on non-chargeable activities.","start":2553.472,"stop":2568.13,"duration":14.66},{"text":"And if you do not object, we will spend whatever amount out of our roughly $40 million budget in the coming year on various activities as we perceive the need, including specifically ballot initiatives, which were specifically mentioned in the notice as one of the things the union spent its money on.","start":2568.13,"stop":2588.043,"duration":19.91},{"text":"Now--","start":2588.043,"stop":2589.145,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought your point, though, was this was a very special ballot initiative.","start":2589.145,"stop":2592.097,"duration":2.95},{"text":"That's what the literature suggests, that this was not sort of the normal run in the courts every two years, every election cycle we spend something.","start":2592.097,"stop":2599.334,"duration":7.24},{"text":"That's why it's a special assessment.","start":2599.334,"stop":2600.703,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I don't -- I wouldn't call it a special assessment if one uses that term as it is usually used, to mean a very short-term assessment apart from general union functions for a new kind of function.","start":2600.703,"stop":2615.879,"duration":15.18}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not short-term; it's just until November 7th or whatever.","start":2615.879,"stop":2617.963,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's nothing new under the sun, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":2617.963,"stop":2620.347,"duration":2.38},{"text":"And we can see that, for example, the record reflects the audit for 2005 shows us that in addition to the money that was attributed to the dues increase and spent in opposing these ballot propositions, additional money, approximately $2 million, was spent on those same purposes from the pre-increase dues.","start":2620.347,"stop":2644.363,"duration":24.02},{"text":"So ballot -- opposing ballot initiatives is nothing new for this scenario -- 17--","start":2644.363,"stop":2649.034,"duration":4.67}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you think for a second to go back to Justice Sotomayor.","start":2649.034,"stop":2651.136,"duration":2.1},{"text":"Now, I would like you to see, I think, why she asked the question.","start":2651.136,"stop":2653.921,"duration":2.78},{"text":"As I understand it, the way it works now is at the beginning of, say, September.","start":2653.921,"stop":2662.074,"duration":8.15},{"text":"September of year 2 we look back to year 1, and we see what the percentages were.","start":2662.074,"stop":2669.613,"duration":7.54},{"text":"And now we in the union calculate a budget for year 2.","start":2669.613,"stop":2673.299,"duration":3.69},{"text":"And we go and get approval or opt-outs on that basis.","start":2673.299,"stop":2678.303,"duration":5},{"text":"Now what I thought coming in here is that the problem was going to be, if you have to have a new notice in the middle of the year for special political assessments, you are going to discover that half the time you don't know if they are special political assessments.","start":2678.303,"stop":2693.313,"duration":15.01},{"text":"It's an impossible line to draw.","start":2693.313,"stop":2695.113,"duration":1.8},{"text":"It's really tough.","start":2695.113,"stop":2696.015,"duration":0.9},{"text":"You are making the argument that however you draw the line, we are on the right side of it, not the wrong side.","start":2696.015,"stop":2701.466,"duration":5.45},{"text":"Isn't that what basically what you are saying, it's not a special assessment, it wasn't really accepted.","start":2701.466,"stop":2706.453,"duration":4.99},{"text":"Okay.","start":2706.453,"stop":2706.87,"duration":0.42},{"text":"Now, but there is a new argument that's come along that I hadn't focused on.","start":2706.87,"stop":2711.107,"duration":4.24},{"text":"If we can avoid the administrative problem by saying all special assessments require a new notice, whether they are for political purposes or not.","start":2711.107,"stop":2723.932,"duration":12.82},{"text":"Hence the question that I was trying to get -- I was very interested in your answer.","start":2723.932,"stop":2728.486,"duration":4.55},{"text":"If we had that rule which avoids the problem of saying which is which, how does that affect the union?","start":2728.486,"stop":2735.556,"duration":7.07},{"text":"Not necessarily yours but unions in general.","start":2735.556,"stop":2738.358,"duration":2.8},{"text":"How often is it that you draw up your budget for year 2 in September, put it into effect, and during the year you discover you need more money from people for any reason, and, therefore, you change what you thought they were going to contribute.","start":2738.358,"stop":2755.469,"duration":17.11},{"text":"How often, if you can give us an estimate, and you are in a better position than I.","start":2755.469,"stop":2759.588,"duration":4.12},{"text":"Does it happen a lot, rarely, a little?","start":2759.588,"stop":2763.992,"duration":4.4},{"text":"What do you want to say?","start":2763.992,"stop":2765.225,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--I -- I--","start":2765.225,"stop":2766.142,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"And a footnote.","start":2766.142,"stop":2766.861,"duration":0.72},{"text":"And it happens a lot, how burdensome is it?","start":2766.861,"stop":2770.063,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--I will get to that, Justice Sotomayor.","start":2770.063,"stop":2771.996,"duration":1.93},{"text":"I have tried to determine how frequent it is, and I have been unable.","start":2771.996,"stop":2776.217,"duration":4.22},{"text":"All I've been able to determine is, there is no litigation over it.","start":2776.217,"stop":2780.019,"duration":3.8},{"text":"How often -- and I have been able to determine that so-called assessments take many different forms from -- and I think there are crucial distinctions from funding what would -- a kind of charge that would not otherwise be funded out of dues for some short period of time to the opposite extreme.","start":2780.019,"stop":2798.213,"duration":18.19},{"text":"What we have here and what I don't think would be called an assessment frankly by anything I've read, a temporary dues increase which became permanent and which simply increased the total flow of dues and fees into the general treasury and which went for the usual, the kinds of activities the union had always funded.","start":2798.213,"stop":2817.377,"duration":19.16},{"text":"And in that regard, there is one--","start":2817.377,"stop":2818.71,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you please answer my question?","start":2818.71,"stop":2820.496,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--The burden.","start":2820.496,"stop":2821.061,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2821.061,"stop":2821.512,"duration":0.45},{"text":"The burden.","start":2821.512,"stop":2822.061,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"The burden consists of two things, Justice Sotomayor.","start":2822.061,"stop":2826.649,"duration":4.59},{"text":"The -- if a union has to give a new Hudson notice in a situation like this whereas I have been trying to explain the spending that went on is really not different from what one would have reasonably anticipated given the notice, then we have litigation and disputes about the need for new notices whenever any number of things happen.","start":2826.649,"stop":2851.265,"duration":24.62},{"text":"Because one thing that happened here that is undisputed but hasn't been discussed is that collective bargaining costs were up six-fold in 2005 over 2004, and they were up six-fold in 2006 over 2005.","start":2851.265,"stop":2866.207,"duration":14.94}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"One reason -- I mean we are dealing with a situation where the union is compelling nonunion members to give them money for political activities.","start":2866.207,"stop":2875.063,"duration":8.86},{"text":"We allow, as I understand Hudson as I read it, because you can't figure out what that is, you wait until the end of the year.","start":2875.063,"stop":2883.919,"duration":8.86},{"text":"In other words, it's a compromise for administrative convenience.","start":2883.919,"stop":2887.371,"duration":3.45},{"text":"Normally you wouldn't allow it at all, as I -- at least under the law as I read it, you would not allow people to take money -- you would not allow the union to take money from people who don't want to spend it on political activities so the union could spend it on political activities.","start":2887.371,"stop":2902.548,"duration":15.18},{"text":"But we allow it during the course of the year because it's impossible as you go on to sort these things out.","start":2902.548,"stop":2908.636,"duration":6.09},{"text":"I thought the argument on the other side was when you have a special assessment, an additional charge, there you don't have the administrative problem.","start":2908.636,"stop":2918.075,"duration":9.44},{"text":"You can tell, it's.25 %.","start":2918.075,"stop":2921.111,"duration":3.04},{"text":"So you can't take that until you tell them, do you want to object or are you happy -- are you fine with having this spent on political purposes?","start":2921.111,"stop":2929.217,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason, Mr. Chief Justice, that it isn't that straight forward is quite simply that all of these questions about it's a special assessment, we can figure out what it is, we can treat it separately, flounder when one realizes that so-called special assessment is simply a dues increase.","start":2929.217,"stop":2953.598,"duration":24.38},{"text":"Because if I were to try to imagine -- let's try to imagine the notice that could have been given.","start":2953.598,"stop":2959.319,"duration":5.72},{"text":"If I were giving a new notice in the fall of 2005 to explain to all nonmembers how things look now compared to what they -- how they may have looked when the Hudson notice was given, I would say the following, completely consistent with all the facts of record in this case as revealed in the audit.","start":2959.319,"stop":2981.4,"duration":22.08},{"text":"I would say: We've determined we need more income.","start":2981.4,"stop":2984.701,"duration":3.3},{"text":"Part of this is because we anticipate $3.7 million in fight-back expenses this year.","start":2984.701,"stop":2991.457,"duration":6.76},{"text":"Another part is we expect more than $3-1/2 dollars of additional bargaining costs this year, and we expect a lot of other changes on our costs.","start":2991.457,"stop":3000.979,"duration":9.52},{"text":"On the Petitioner's theory, and this is why Schermerhorn is the complete answer to their theory, there is a constitutional violation if the union says: We are going to view this increase as paying for our additional political costs, and it's going to free up our bargaining -- our general treasury for the bargaining.","start":3000.979,"stop":3022.243,"duration":21.26},{"text":"That's a violation.","start":3022.243,"stop":3023.643,"duration":1.4},{"text":"But if you say: We are going to treat this increase as covering those new bargaining costs we told you about, that's going to free up our general treasury for the political costs.","start":3023.643,"stop":3032.7,"duration":9.06}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But, I mean -- I'm reading from the district court opinion.","start":3032.7,"stop":3035.902,"duration":3.2},{"text":"It said that this assessment would be used, and they are quoting from union material,","start":3035.902,"stop":3040.854,"duration":4.95},{"text":"\"for a broad range of political expenses, including television, radio advertising, direct mail, voter registration, voter education, and get-out-the-vote activity in our work sites and in communities across California. \"","start":3040.854,"stop":3053.696,"duration":12.84},{"text":"And it further said,","start":3053.696,"stop":3055.246,"duration":1.55},{"text":"\"The fund will not be used for regular costs of the union such as office rent, staff salaries, or routine equipment replacement. \"","start":3055.246,"stop":3062.569,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"But two points, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3062.569,"stop":3064.752,"duration":2.18},{"text":"First, as the Court of Appeals pointed out, there were other statements that said the money would be used for both purposes.","start":3064.752,"stop":3070.373,"duration":5.62},{"text":"But as Schermerhorn points out, Schermerhorn says even if you specifically say this part of our dues income is going to be earmarked for this purpose, it's artificial when you're dealing with a general union treasury, not a separate segregated fund, to give that separate legal status.","start":3070.373,"stop":3092.822,"duration":22.45},{"text":"And that -- because that is why -- my point to you, Mr. Chief Justice, is nothing in the world would have changed here.","start":3092.822,"stop":3100.492,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose -- suppose that the proponents of Propositions 75 and 76 had come to the union and said, would you please give us an interest-free loan for money, because we want to use this money to -- to persuade the -- the electorate to enact these, but don't worry, because we're going to pay it back right after the election, when we've achieved our electoral ends.","start":3100.492,"stop":3124.976,"duration":24.48},{"text":"Would -- would the union provide the money because it's all going to come out in the wash?","start":3124.976,"stop":3128.845,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I really can't answer that question.","start":3128.845,"stop":3136.933,"duration":8.09},{"text":"I don't know.","start":3136.933,"stop":3137.483,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- gee, I really doubt that you -- that they would.","start":3137.483,"stop":3141.052,"duration":3.57},{"text":"But what's the difference?","start":3141.052,"stop":3142.004,"duration":0.95},{"text":"If you look at this from the perspective of a nonmember who doesn't want those ballot initiatives to be defeated, saying that we're going to give you your money back.","start":3142.004,"stop":3152.543,"duration":10.54},{"text":"We're going to use your money to achieve a political end that you oppose, but don't worry, because we're going to give it back to you next year after we've achieved our political end.","start":3152.543,"stop":3162.585,"duration":10.04},{"text":"How does that solve the problem?","start":3162.585,"stop":3164.285,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not the situation here, Justice Alito.","start":3164.285,"stop":3165.953,"duration":1.67},{"text":"The nonmembers were told in June 2005 in the Hudson notice that if you don't object, we may spend millions of dollars on political activities, including ballot initiatives.","start":3165.953,"stop":3176.825,"duration":10.87},{"text":"If a person didn't want to support that, they merely needed to object.","start":3176.825,"stop":3181.212,"duration":4.39},{"text":"But what then happened -- and this is what gets lost in the messaging about the dues increase -- what actually happened in the real world in the period that followed is that compared to the numbers in the 2004 Hudson notice, the union spent less on nonchargeable matters and more on chargeable matters, and the only reason there's a case here in the Court is that the union, for whatever PR purposes, whatever it may have been, instead of saying, we're going to treat the increase as covering our vastly increased bargaining costs, thereby freeing up money for politics, we're instead going to describe this increase as being attributable to our political costs, thereby freeing up money for bargaining.","start":3181.212,"stop":3228.257,"duration":47.05},{"text":"But what the union is spending its money on is bargaining.","start":3228.257,"stop":3232.895,"duration":4.64},{"text":"More money--","start":3232.895,"stop":3234.161,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it seems to me that this answer is, it's so confusing that the Court probably should consider whether or not an opt-in requirement is -- is preferable.","start":3234.161,"stop":3245.468,"duration":11.31},{"text":"I -- we're talking, in the first exchange, you had with Justice Alito, he gave you a very simple question: 90 percent, 10 percent.","start":3245.468,"stop":3253.824,"duration":8.36},{"text":"Then, it's reversed.","start":3253.824,"stop":3254.641,"duration":0.82},{"text":"Special assessment for 90 percent political.","start":3254.641,"stop":3257.51,"duration":2.87},{"text":"And the point there was that you're taking someone's money contrary to that person's conscience.","start":3257.51,"stop":3264.199,"duration":6.69},{"text":"And that's what the First Amendment stands against.","start":3264.199,"stop":3266.599,"duration":2.4},{"text":"And you simply wouldn't answer that question.","start":3266.599,"stop":3269.234,"duration":2.63},{"text":"You would -- and then you say well, maybe it's -- it's fungible, it's hard to -- it seems to me that you're avoiding a very, very critical question on the constitutional rights of these objecting members.","start":3269.234,"stop":3281.042,"duration":11.81}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--I won't avoid the -- I don't believe -- I was not meaning to avoid it, Justice Kennedy.","start":3281.042,"stop":3284.695,"duration":3.65},{"text":"What I thought I said is, if you are springing something on someone that's not anticipated in the notice that gave them their rights to object, then there's a problem.","start":3284.695,"stop":3293.801,"duration":9.11},{"text":"My point is very simple.","start":3293.801,"stop":3295.168,"duration":1.37},{"text":"Anyone reading the 2005 notice -- Hudson notice, if that person was asked -- if I -- if I don't object, might the union spend $3.7 million next year on ballot initiatives that I may not want to oppose?","start":3295.168,"stop":3312.263,"duration":17.09},{"text":"The answer would be yes.","start":3312.263,"stop":3313.563,"duration":1.3},{"text":"The notice made it perfectly clear--","start":3313.563,"stop":3315.565,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask you this, just in the way of background: In collective bargaining negotiations, do the unions consider the -- as one factor the importance of ensuring that the government or employer has fiscal stability?","start":3315.565,"stop":3332.676,"duration":17.11}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's generally considered, yes.","start":3332.676,"stop":3335.478,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that ultimately a political judgment, so that even collective bargaining involves a core political judgment?","start":3335.478,"stop":3343.282,"duration":7.8}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's exactly what the Court said in Abood.","start":3343.282,"stop":3345.668,"duration":2.39},{"text":"And the reason that exclusivity and agency fees are permitted in -- in serving an important government purpose is that the government has concluded that its interest lies in having an exclusive spokesperson who -- with whom it can negotiate so that it won't have an array of different employment relations or concerns.","start":3345.668,"stop":3367.183,"duration":21.51}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But you -- you concede then in ordinary collective bargaining, there are critical and important significant political judgments that are being made by the union in the course of collective bargaining with chargeable expenses?","start":3367.183,"stop":3381.091,"duration":13.91}]},{"speakerName":"Jeremiah Collins","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":3381.091,"stop":3381.841,"duration":0.75},{"text":"And Abood explicitly says that.","start":3381.841,"stop":3383.876,"duration":2.04},{"text":"And Abood then says that nevertheless, the government -- we're talking about a regulatory scheme to promote the government's interest in orderly labor relations -- the government needs to make arrangements and agreements on terms of employment; it has a vital interest in having an exclusive representational arrangement where that can be accomplished.","start":3383.876,"stop":3407.658,"duration":23.78},{"text":"And that, the Court held in Abood -- and it's not challenged by Petitioners -- that justifies the degree of impingement that is inherent in the fact that, as Your Honor correctly says, all bargaining, particularly in the public sector, has political elements in it.","start":3407.658,"stop":3423.52,"duration":15.86}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3423.52,"stop":3424.286,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3424.286,"stop":3429.424,"duration":5.14}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Young, I hope this won't use up much of your time, but I do have a pressing question to make sure that we're just not spinning our wheels here.","start":3429.424,"stop":3436.078,"duration":6.65},{"text":"What if the union here had -- had simply said all this additional assessment will go to bargaining activities, and then simply used its original assessment, the portion that had been anticipated to be used for bargaining, for political activities.","start":3436.078,"stop":3458.591,"duration":22.51},{"text":"It could do that, couldn't it?","start":3458.591,"stop":3459.609,"duration":1.02},{"text":"It's not committed to -- to, you know, an 80-20 or whatever the division is, simply because that's what's given out in the first notice.","start":3459.609,"stop":3468.299,"duration":8.69},{"text":"It can indeed use its -- the anticipated portion for bargaining for political activities?","start":3468.299,"stop":3475.703,"duration":7.4}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be free to do so, Justice Scalia.","start":3475.703,"stop":3477.905,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"So why are we wasting our time?","start":3477.905,"stop":3478.955,"duration":1.05},{"text":"I mean, all the unions are going to do is say this is a general assessment for bargaining purposes, and then use their -- their general funds for the political thing.","start":3478.955,"stop":3487.443,"duration":8.49}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the nonmembers still have that right to challenge, Justice Scalia.","start":3487.443,"stop":3491.414,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But they don't lose it; they're going to do it the following September.","start":3491.414,"stop":3494.782,"duration":3.37},{"text":"The attractive part of your argument from the beginning was that this is somehow a forced loan.","start":3494.782,"stop":3502.203,"duration":7.42},{"text":"And I understand the attractiveness of that.","start":3502.203,"stop":3505.238,"duration":3.03},{"text":"But it goes back to what Justice Breyer said from the beginning, which is, given -- as has been recognized, that money is fungible, and that you can't really often predict what's going to happen in the future, it's been developed a system that cyclically gets money to the people back.","start":3505.238,"stop":3527.17,"duration":21.93}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"And money is fungible to a degree, Justice Sotomayor -- Sotomayor -- excuse me.","start":3527.17,"stop":3533.407,"duration":6.24},{"text":"And I respect that argument.","start":3533.407,"stop":3535.041,"duration":1.63},{"text":"But let's remember the facts as we have them here.","start":3535.041,"stop":3537.793,"duration":2.75},{"text":"In the facts of this case, it was a segregated fund.","start":3537.793,"stop":3540.911,"duration":3.12},{"text":"There's a separate portion, a separate line item in the union's notice--","start":3540.911,"stop":3544.965,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":3544.965,"stop":3545.615,"duration":0.65},{"text":"So you win and it will never happen again.","start":3545.615,"stop":3547.501,"duration":1.89},{"text":"It'll never again be called a segregated fund for politics.","start":3547.501,"stop":3551.786,"duration":4.28},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":3551.786,"stop":3552.586,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--I lose, Justice Scalia, and it will happen all the time, I'm afraid.","start":3552.586,"stop":3555.571,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but the -- the problem if you win in this case, and then there is this other way of getting to the same -- the same result -- is that the other way of getting to the same -- same result, while permissible, is far less transparent.","start":3555.571,"stop":3571.866,"duration":16.3},{"text":"And people won't understand it, and it -- it encourages a kind of slyness that seems highly undesirable.","start":3571.866,"stop":3580.805,"duration":8.94},{"text":"And the virtue of the present system is that it does require some forced loans, that's true, but it does wash out in the wash, and it ends up being fair to the objectors.","start":3580.805,"stop":3595.065,"duration":14.26},{"text":"And it's simply hard to think of a better system that doesn't provide more administrative problems than the existing one.","start":3595.065,"stop":3604.171,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"But--","start":3604.171,"stop":3605.121,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So that's -- go ahead.","start":3605.121,"stop":3606.622,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"--And I thank you, Justice Breyer.","start":3606.622,"stop":3607.772,"duration":1.15},{"text":"I'm sorry for interrupting.","start":3607.772,"stop":3608.922,"duration":1.15},{"text":"I understand that, Justice.","start":3608.922,"stop":3610.924,"duration":2},{"text":"And for ordinary union dues, that's why when Justice Sotomayor asked me at the beginning of the argument whether we're challenging the ordinary Hudson system, I answered no, because that system is perfectly adequate for ordinary union dues.","start":3610.924,"stop":3624.751,"duration":13.83}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"The problem is that I am being told by your adversary, and since we don't know, I'm always afraid of writing a decision in a vacuum, okay?","start":3624.751,"stop":3633.69,"duration":8.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":3633.69,"stop":3634.157,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"That union structure, their business in a myriad number of ways, that some have a very small due each year, and a larger special assessment for special projects.","start":3634.157,"stop":3648.449,"duration":14.29},{"text":"And I assume there's endless variety.","start":3648.449,"stop":3650.818,"duration":2.37},{"text":"You're proposing a rule that every single time an assessment outside of annual dues is imposed, that a new Hudson notice can be given.","start":3650.818,"stop":3663.959,"duration":13.14},{"text":"And you're suggesting Justice Scalia, that all they have to say is we think it's going to be for chargeable effect.","start":3663.959,"stop":3673.415,"duration":9.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the issue -- I'm sorry.","start":3673.415,"stop":3675.034,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Briefly, counsel.","start":3675.034,"stop":3676.267,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Young","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3676.267,"stop":3677.902,"duration":1.64},{"text":"So Justice Sotomayor, the answer is that I'm saying it would be brief -- and my friend Mr. Collins is saying that it doesn't happen that often, so the burden is minimal.","start":3677.902,"stop":3689.776,"duration":11.87},{"text":"Unions have other options than extracting this money from unwitting nonmembers, through interest-free loans.","start":3689.776,"stop":3695.847,"duration":6.07},{"text":"And I thank the Court.","start":3695.847,"stop":3696.547,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3696.547,"stop":3697.18,"duration":0.63},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3697.18,"stop":3698.465,"duration":1.29}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Jan 10, 2012","petitioner":"Dianne Knox, et al.","respondent":"Service Employees International Union, Local 1000","docket":"10-1121","citation":"567 US _ (2012)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/567/10-1121","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit","grantedOn":"Jun 27, 2011","decidedOn":"Jun 21, 2012"}